<subSubSection id="C37089B0B831521F78835DE8FC5A28DF" pageId="17" pageNumber="1050" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph id="8BD5DA3BB831521F78835DE8FE862F90" blockId="17.[160,333,921,947]" box="[160,333,921,947]" pageId="17" pageNumber="1050">
<heading id="D09D6D57B831521F78835DE8FE862F90" bold="true" box="[160,333,921,947]" centered="true" fontSize="11" level="2" pageId="17" pageNumber="1050" reason="3">
<taxonomicName id="4C6AA1B8B831521F78835DE8FE862F90" authorityName=", Bryk" authorityYear="1935" box="[160,333,921,947]" class="Insecta" family="Papilionidae" genus="Hypermnestra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="1050" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B91E0629B831521F78835DE8FE862F90" bold="true" box="[160,333,921,947]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1050">Hypermnestra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD5DA3BB831521F78835DBFFC5A28DF" blockId="17.[160,1156,974,1727]" pageId="17" pageNumber="1050">
The sphragis of 
<taxonomicName id="4C6AA1B8B831521F797B5DBFFE3B2FC4" authorityName=", Bryk" authorityYear="1935" box="[344,496,974,999]" class="Insecta" family="Papilionidae" genus="Hypermnestra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="1050" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B91E0629B831521F797B5DBFFE3B2FC4" box="[344,496,974,999]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1050">Hypermnestra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a mass of unformed male secretion, but it may appear somewhat structured due to its overlaying the unusual external female genitalia, with a fleshy projection just behind the ostium, on which the thick coat of secretion forms a still more projecting sphragis. We consider the sphragis in 
<taxonomicName id="4C6AA1B8B831521F7BAA5A47FBEA286C" authorityName=", Bryk" authorityYear="1935" box="[905,1057,1078,1103]" class="Insecta" family="Papilionidae" genus="Hypermnestra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="1050" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B91E0629B831521F7BAA5A47FBEA286C" box="[905,1057,1078,1103]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1050">Hypermnestra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to be a protosphragis, because of its irregular and crude formation; moreover, there is no sclerotisation of the female external genitalia (sterigma) and the ostium bursae is not exposed as in typical sphragis-bearing species. The lack of sharp or stout recurved structures on the male genitalia that might be used for sphragis removal also supports the view that 
<taxonomicName id="4C6AA1B8B831521F791E5A92FE1E28DF" authorityName=", Bryk" authorityYear="1935" box="[317,469,1251,1276]" class="Insecta" family="Papilionidae" genus="Hypermnestra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="1050" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B91E0629B831521F791E5A92FE1E28DF" box="[317,469,1251,1276]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1050">Hypermnestra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is at early stage of evolving a sphragis.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C37089B0B831521C78E35B77FECE2F34" lastPageId="18" lastPageNumber="1051" pageId="17" pageNumber="1050" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BD5DA3BB831521C78E35B77FECE2F34" blockId="17.[160,1156,974,1727]" lastBlockId="18.[160,1156,142,791]" lastPageId="18" lastPageNumber="1051" pageId="17" pageNumber="1050">
The sterigma of female 
<taxonomicName id="4C6AA1B8B831521F79E55B77FD95293C" authorityName=", Bryk" authorityYear="1935" box="[454,606,1286,1311]" class="Insecta" family="Papilionidae" genus="Hypermnestra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="1050" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B91E0629B831521F79E55B77FD95293C" box="[454,606,1286,1311]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1050">Hypermnestra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is not obviously specialised to reject plugging by the male but is highly modified from the ancestral condition found in most non-sphragisbearing butterflies and the ostium is still rather exposed. Moreover, the fleshy projection seems to support the sphragis. The projection itself is relatively soft (at least when macerated), but after a male smears it with a large amount of secretory material, it provides a core, supporting a sphragis at the right angle to the abdomen to create an obstacle to remating with another male. If so, the female genitalia of 
<taxonomicName id="4C6AA1B8B831521F7B975BA7FB8729CC" authorityName=", Bryk" authorityYear="1935" box="[948,1100,1494,1519]" class="Insecta" family="Papilionidae" genus="Hypermnestra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="1050" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B91E0629B831521F7B975BA7FB8729CC" box="[948,1100,1494,1519]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1050">Hypermnestra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may be secondarily adapted to retain a sphragis. Possibly the females actively grip a small sphragis that will inhibit remating; in this way they might receive a larger spermatophore. Probable sphragis-retaining female genitalia among sphragis-bearing 
<taxonomicName id="4C6AA1B8B831521F7BE8584FFB9E2A74" box="[971,1109,1598,1623]" class="Insecta" family="Papilionidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="1050" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Papilionidae</taxonomicName>
are otherwise only known in 
<taxonomicName id="4C6AA1B8B831521F79965810FD032A59" authority="(Hubner)" baseAuthorityName="Hubner" baseAuthorityYear="1831" box="[437,712,1633,1658]" class="Insecta" family="Papilionidae" genus="Parides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="1050" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="proneus">
<emphasis id="B91E0629B831521F79965810FDAB2A59" box="[437,608,1633,1658]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1050">Parides proneus</emphasis>
(HÃ¼bner)
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFFBA7CAB831521F7AF05810FCFE2A59" author="Orr AG" box="[723,821,1633,1658]" pageId="17" pageNumber="1050" refId="ref11999" refString="Orr AG. 1988. Mate conflict and the evolution of the sphragis in butterflies [dissertation]. Nathan: Griffith University." type="book" year="1988">Orr 1988</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFFBA7CAB831521F7B1C5810FCBD2A59" author="Orr AG" box="[831,886,1633,1658]" pageId="17" pageNumber="1050" pagination="155 - 164" refId="ref12023" refString="Orr AG. 1995. The evolution of the sphragis in the Papilionidae and other butterflies. In: Scriber JM, Tsubaki Y, Lederhouse RC, editors. Swallowtail butterflies: their ecology and evolutionary biology. Gainesville: Scientific Publishers; p. 155 - 164." type="book chapter" year="1995">1995</bibRefCitation>
). The female genitalia in this species are exposed but equipped with a sclerotised bar in front of the ostium, which anchors a small sphragis. It is possible that this is a female adaptation to retain the sphragis meaning that a small sphragis is still effective, thus enabling males to commit more secretory material to a large spermatophore. In general, it is possible that in certain circumstances females evolve the capacity to hold a sphragis when additional matings are no longer advantageous. This may be because the male has already provided a significant nuptial gift, together with the small sphragis, or, in cases where male ejaculates are small and spermatophores have little nutritional value, bearing a sphragis may free a female from the risks and costs of unwanted copulation (i.e. waste of time and energy, risk of predation or physical damage). 
<bibRefCitation id="EFFBA7CAB832521C7A2D5FF0FCEE2DB9" author="Orr AG &amp; Rutowski RL" box="[526,805,385,410]" pageId="18" pageNumber="1051" pagination="703 - 710" refId="ref12169" refString="Orr AG, Rutowski RL. 1991. The function of the sphragis in Cressida cressida (Fab.) (Lepidoptera, Papilionidae): a visual deterrent to copulation attempts. J Nat Hist. 25: 703 - 710. doi: 10.1080 / 00222939100770461." type="journal article" year="1991">Orr and Rutowski (1991)</bibRefCitation>
demonstrated that females of 
<taxonomicName id="4C6AA1B8B832521C78835FD5FE9E2D9E" authority="cressida" box="[160,341,420,445]" class="Insecta" family="Papilionidae" genus="Cressida" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="1051" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cressida">
<emphasis id="B91E0629B832521C78835FD5FE9E2D9E" box="[160,341,420,445]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="1051">Cressida cressida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which receive no nutrients from the male (
<bibRefCitation id="EFFBA7CAB832521C7B115FD5FC5F2D9E" author="Orr AG" box="[818,916,420,445]" pageId="18" pageNumber="1051" refId="ref11999" refString="Orr AG. 1988. Mate conflict and the evolution of the sphragis in butterflies [dissertation]. Nathan: Griffith University." type="book" year="1988">Orr 1988</bibRefCitation>
), display the sphragis to avoid unwanted second matings, which in this species may prove fatal (
<bibRefCitation id="EFFBA7CAB832521C7C2C5FB7FBBD2DFC" author="Orr AG" box="[1039,1142,454,479]" pageId="18" pageNumber="1051" pagination="115 - 134" refId="ref12073" refString="Orr AG. 1999. The big greasy, Cressida cressida (Papilionidae). In: Kitching RL, Scheermeyer E, Jones RE, Pierce NE, editors. Monographs on Australian Lepidoptera 6: biology of Australian butterflies. Collingswood: CSIRO Publishing; p. 115 - 134." type="book chapter" year="1999">Orr 1999</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation id="EFFBA7CAB832521C78835F98FE4E2E21" author="Wedell N &amp; Wiklund C &amp; Cook PA" box="[160,389,489,514]" pageId="18" pageNumber="1051" pagination="450 - 455" refId="ref13030" refString="Wedell N, Wiklund C, Cook PA. 2002. Monoandry and polyandry as alternative lifestyles in a butterfly. Behav Ecol. 13: 450 - 455. doi: 10.1093 / beheco / 13.4.450." type="journal article" year="2002">Wedell et al. (2002)</bibRefCitation>
demonstrated that there is a genetic variation in female mating frequency in 
<taxonomicName id="4C6AA1B8B832521C791B5C7DFDEC2E06" authority="(Linnaeus)" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[312,551,524,549]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ericaceae" genus="Pieris" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="18" pageNumber="1051" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="napi">
<emphasis id="B91E0629B832521C791B5C7DFE612E06" box="[312,426,524,549]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="1051">Pieris napi</emphasis>
(Linnaeus)
</taxonomicName>
in 
<collectingCountry id="F37D9AABB832521C7A6C5C7DFD632E06" box="[591,680,524,549]" name="Sweden" pageId="18" pageNumber="1051">Sweden</collectingCountry>
and suggested that the variation can be related to a trade-off between the nutritional benefit and time available for oviposition in the unpredictable Swedish weather. Mated female 
<taxonomicName id="4C6AA1B8B832521C7AD35C20FC842E49" baseAuthorityName="Nickerl" baseAuthorityYear="1846" box="[752,847,593,618]" class="Insecta" family="Papilionidae" genus="Hypermnestra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="1051" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="helios">
<emphasis id="B91E0629B832521C7AD35C20FC842E49" box="[752,847,593,618]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="1051">H. helios</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may benefit from bearing a sphragis while ovipositing, because the species lives in a dry open habitat and females lay eggs singly on a small hostplant (
<bibRefCitation id="EFFBA7CAB832521C7A605CE7FD102E8C" author="Igarashi S" box="[579,731,662,687]" pageId="18" pageNumber="1051" refId="ref11265" refString="Igarashi S. 1979. Papilionidae and their early stages. Tokyo: Kodansha." type="book" year="1979">Igarashi 1979</bibRefCitation>
), hence ovipositing females probably conspicuously visit many hostplants and they may frequently encounter and be harassed by searching males, a situation where the female may benefit by retaining an effective sphragis.
</paragraph>
